    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-rh-index-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Relative Hemolysis Index Comparison Against FDA Pump Experimental Benchmark",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RH) values were compared against experimentally measured hemolysis data from the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump test campaign. Across all five flow-speed operating points (Q = 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 L/min at 2500 RPM and 3500 RPM), the CFD model produced RH predictions within ±12% of experimental measurements. The worst-case operating condition was consistently identified as Q = 2 L/min at 3500 RPM, with a predicted RH of 0.87 against the predicate device baseline, satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. The simulation campaign was executed using ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 with a k-ω SST turbulence closure, a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation model (Giersiepen coefficients), and a polyhedral mesh of approximately 4.2 million cells confirmed converged through a three-level mesh refinement study. Blood viscosity was set at 0.0035 Pa·s (Newtonian approximation, justified by high shear rates in the impeller region). Boundary conditions were derived from the experimental test loop pressure-flow curves provided in the FDA benchmark dataset. Residual convergence to below 1×10⁻⁵ for all transport equations was verified for each operating point. The experimental data were collected by an independent laboratory under ISO 10993-4 compliant protocols, with triplicate measurements at each operating condition. Agreement between CFD and experiment is considered sufficient to support MRL 2 validation requirements for the quantity of interest.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-hemolysis"
    },
